<!-- ── HISTORY ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<section>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="history-block">
      <p>
        Summitville Wesleyan Bible Church was founded in August 1874 as the
        Summitville Wesleyan Methodist Church, organized in a log cabin with
        40 members. Rev. Isaac Meeks served as the first pastor. In 1878, the
        congregation built its first church building on Church Street, with
        members cutting and hauling timber from the woods to construct it by hand.
      </p>
      <p>
        Through the late 1800s and early 1900s, the church weathered seasons of
        hardship and seasons of revival. In 1904, under Rev. W.L. Thompson, a
        powerful revival brought approximately forty young people to faith. In
        1920, under Rev. E.J. Mills, the church experienced what many called its
        greatest revival, with the congregation growing so large they had to move
        services to the McCaslin sale barn. The first Vacation Bible School was
        launched in 1943, and the church continued to grow through the mid-20th
        century, reaching a record of 180 in Sunday School attendance in the 1950s.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 1968, the church merged with the Pilgrim Holiness Church and became
        part of the Wesleyan Church denomination. Then in November 1983, after
        much prayer, the congregation made the decision to become independent,
        purchasing all church properties from the denomination and taking the name
        Wesleyan Bible Holiness Church. The church celebrated its centennial in
        1974 and continued to grow under the long tenure of Rev. James Meek
        (1974-1987), during which four young men from the congregation were called
        into full-time ministry.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 1990, ground was broken for a new church building at its current
        location north of town. The congregation, including women and children,
        worked together through the construction. The building was completed and
        the church moved in under the leadership of Rev. Mark Cravens. Rev.
        Danny Decker arrived as pastor in March 2003 and has served faithfully
        ever since. During his tenure, the Family Ministry Center was built and
        paid off debt-free, numerous facility improvements were made, and Pastor
        Decker has worked to unite the churches of Summitville in shared worship
        and service. In 2021, Brent Kirby joined the staff as Youth Pastor.
      </p>
      <p>
        For nearly 150 years, God has been faithful to this congregation through
        times of growth and challenge alike. We are grateful for every person who
        has shaped this church's story, and we look forward to what God will
        write in the chapters still to come.
      </p>

